{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 16:23:03", "language": "en", "author": "31411", "url": "http://lokeshshah.wordpress.com/?p=747", "title": "Gulmohars in Bloom", "blog": "31394", "post_id": "1599518", "tags": ["Photography"], "blogname": "Do Anna Blog", "date": "2012-05-01 21:53:03", "content": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"1124\" caption=\"Hope Farm Junction to Old Madras Road\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_007-Frame by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6978788784/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8021/6978788784_b54f116112_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_007-Frame\" width=\"1124\" height=\"1025\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"1124\" caption=\"Hoskote - Malur Road\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_030-Frame by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6978788496/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7080/6978788496_c018039407_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_030-Frame\" width=\"1124\" height=\"999\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "categories": ["General"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 15:30:24", "language": "en", "author": "31411", "url": "http://lokeshshah.wordpress.com/?p=743", "title": "Bike Ride (Gulmohar Blooms) \u2013 Apr 2012", "blog": "31394", "post_id": "477178", "tags": ["bike ride"], "blogname": "Do Anna Blog", "date": "2012-05-02 21:00:24", "content": "Gulmohars are in bloom and the lure of hitting the tarmac was omnipresent. After toying around with google maps for a route, I decided to take the Malur road and extend it via KGF to Krishnagiri and back.\r\nBelow is the route I ended up taking. Good choice for a ride; bad for photography.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"Route Map\"]<a title=\"map by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127230377/\"><img title=\"Route Map\" src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7131/7127230377_1c257a3a46_c.jpg\" alt=\"map\" width=\"800\" height=\"561\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nLeft home a little later than usual for there to be enough light for the photos. Canon S90 is not really knows for its high ISO quality. The image below shows that clearly.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"First glimpse of the Gulmohars. The sun still hasn't risen and the grey horizon makes for bad light for photos.\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_002 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6981142010/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7206/6981142010_8355c586cb_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_002\" width=\"800\" height=\"599\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"This is what I was hoping to photograph. Had to ride again in the evening to take this pic.\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_007 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6981142148/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8150/6981142148_750449f33b_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_007\" width=\"800\" height=\"722\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nFirst stop for photos lit a bulb in my head. How could I have not thought of it? The first part (i.e., morning hours) of the ride, I was heading east; into the rising sun. The light would be coming from the wring direction. Plus I was still too early for the sun and Gulmohar combo to paint the view scarlet red.\r\nMaking a mental note to come back at sundown soon, I head on to NH4 and after hitting Hoskote, turned right under the 2nd flyover. The road on the left goes to Chintamani. <a href=\"http://lokeshshah.wordpress.com/2011/09/25/bike-ride-horsley-foothills-sep-2011/\" target=\"_blank\">A pleasant route. I have fond memories of that ride, first decent ride on the Avy 220</a>.\r\nThe road to Malur is in excellent condition. The Gulmohars are in full bloom. Few photos below from a sunset ride I did just to photograph the blooms.\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_030 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6981144198/\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8150/6981144198_e38bd9fa5a_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_030\" width=\"800\" height=\"703\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_034-2 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127230491/\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7225/7127230491_c51d750a83_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_034-2\" width=\"585\" height=\"800\" /></a></p>\r\nPast Malur, I head towards Bangarpet. The road is patchy; pretty bad in some stretches and decent in other. The terrain turned dry and shrubby. The tree lined road gives way to a dusty one. Rocky outcrops dot the landscape.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"Rocky outcrop past Tekal\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_024 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/6981144422/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8142/6981144422_a4b1eb527e_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_024\" width=\"800\" height=\"512\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nIt is still early in the morning, so the sun beating down from above is still bearable.\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_026 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127230133/\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8165/7127230133_b49d353fcf_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_026\" width=\"800\" height=\"745\" /></a></p>\r\nPausing to rest under a hard to find tree, I realise another mistake. No water bottle. I was glad this was a short ride through populated terrain. Water would be easy to find.\r\n\r\nAfter a tea break at Bangarpet, I head on towards the KGF area. Flowering trees make a come back, probably planted by the KGF people.\r\n\r\nPost Kotilingeshwara the desolate landscape resumes. Searching for a shady tree, I find one after several Km and stop for a short break.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"A little rest under shady tree\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_032 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127229539/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8148/7127229539_816dd449ab_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_032\" width=\"800\" height=\"631\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nNext I have to take left at Venkatagirikota. There are a few people on the road and none could confirm that I am on the right road to Venkatagirikota. After asking 5-6 people, I realise I should be asking for V.Kota. Everyone knew about V,Kota and I get confirmation that I am heading in the right direction.\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">V.Kota is a decent sized city and I take a right turn towards Krishnagiri.\r\nFinding a Hetitage Parlour I stop for some cold Badam milk before heading on.\r\n<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_034 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127229417/\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7256/7127229417_8266322464_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_034\" width=\"800\" height=\"792\" /></a></p>\r\nThe road is excellent till Krishnagiri with very few small bad stretches. The terrain is still not pretty, though the road is mostly lined with shade giving trees.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"800\" caption=\"Rocky Terrain\"]<a title=\"BikeRideGulmohar_036 by Lokesh Shah, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/lshah/7127230697/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7186/7127230697_45ea3f9dbf_o.jpg\" alt=\"BikeRideGulmohar_036\" width=\"800\" height=\"505\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nFrom Krishnagiri, it is a home stretch on NH-7, but at Shoolkagiri I decide to take a twist. I know an alternate route home and so turn right towards Berikai.\r\nPuri and coffee at Berikai for breakfast. Puri was a bad choice as I struggled to push the cold dry puri down my throat.\r\n\r\nBerikai to Bagalur is a nice road. At Bagalur there is a bridge under construction where only 2 wheelers can pass. Been like that for months.\r\nPast Bagalur, I realise that there was some rattling noise on the front side. A funny rattle every time I hit a bump. Stopped to investigate but could not figure out much.\r\nBagalur to Sarjapur and then to Whitefield via Chikkatirupati. The well laid road leads to a nice ride.\r\n290Km and home by 2PM.", "categories": ["General"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 00:19:19", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2602", "title": "Church Cove, East Coast Trail", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1394792", "tags": ["Church Cove", "East Coast Trail", "family", "fitness", "flatrock", "hiking", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "Nikon D70", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "photos", "spring", "Stairway", "torbay", "trail"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-04-29 21:49:19", "content": "If you walk along the <a href=\"http://eastcoasttrail.ca/\">East Coast Trail</a> between Flatrock and Torbay, you will come intersections at both the Torbay and Flatrock ends at which you are given two choices: \"East Coast Trail difficult\" and \"East Coast Trail via the Father Troy Path.\"\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"Looking from Church Cove toward Torbay and (ultimately) St. John's. Cabot Tower is there on the horizon (although it's tricky to see).\"]<a title=\"A Large Day by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6980226036/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7221/6980226036_f6871990f2_z.jpg\" alt=\"A Large Day\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nShould you opt to follow in the good father's footsteps, you will wend your way through lovely forests and mature-growth stands of spruce and fir. It is a peaceful walk and easy on the soles.\r\n\r\nIf, however, you opt to take the difficult route, you will experience a rather dramatic adventure of the mind and feet, which, while not easy on the soles, certainly rejuvenates the soul (in the manner of all good near-death experiences).\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"532\" caption=\"Cliff Face at the top of Church Cove, before descending the astonishing and somewhat scary stone steps.\"]<a title=\"Cliff Face by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6980232734/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7246/6980232734_e9e33cb925_c.jpg\" alt=\"Cliff Face\" width=\"532\" height=\"800\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe talented trail crew of the East Coast Trail Association has engineered the most remarkable set of stairs by rearranging the existing rocks into incredibly stable and beautifully camouflaged trail that starts at the top of Church Cove and drops you down, down, down, down over boulders and staircases and more boulders and path and then more stairs.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"The reward for perseverance and climbing about a million steps.\"]<a title=\"Gull Play by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6980234358/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7114/6980234358_a673ee5fd0_z.jpg\" alt=\"Gull Play\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nIf it weren't for the markers, you'd never know there was a route through the boulders just by looking. Going down is a little heart-stopping in spots, particularly on the wooden, log-hewn, stairs which run at about a 70-degree angle at times.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"426\" caption=\"Trail marker amid the stones.\"]<a title=\"Stone Stairs by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7126316827/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7122/7126316827_689e474692_z.jpg\" alt=\"Stone Stairs\" width=\"426\" height=\"640\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">My hat is off to these folks. I'm not sure how they envisioned a trail running almost vertically down a near-cliff, but somehow they managed not only the vision, but the reality and a fairly safe version of it at that.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"426\" caption=\"Katherine and John pause for a look at the view.\"]<a title=\"A Long Way Down by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7126314173/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7191/7126314173_c258eacc44_z.jpg\" alt=\"A Long Way Down\" width=\"426\" height=\"640\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">And at the bottom of the stairs, nestled in a little valley, a waterfall....</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"591\" caption=\"An oasis of mossy green and spring abundance\"]<a title=\"Oasis by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7126323439/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7113/7126323439_b861b7fab3_z.jpg\" alt=\"Oasis\" width=\"591\" height=\"640\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Like all good challenges, this one has its rewards....</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"The rocks running parallel across the middle are the stone pathway across the brook. I crouched downstream for this exposure.\"]<a title=\"Spring Stream by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7126321957/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7205/7126321957_db9df2664a_z.jpg\" alt=\"Spring Stream\" width=\"640\" height=\"470\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">If you haven't yet gone out there, do! You can access the trail from either end, as well as from a dirt path that connects straight to Church Cove, starting just off Wind Gap road, as Windgap starts to drop into Flatrock. If you need more trail info, I strongly recommend that you pick up a set of the <a href=\"http://eastcoasttrail.ca/trail_shop/view.php?id=4\">East Coast Trail maps</a>, which contain all sorts of useful info about access points, places along the trail worth seeing, and many other noteworthy gems of knowledge.</p>", "categories": ["hiking", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "nikon D70", "photography", "photos", "Travel"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 15:46:11", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2605", "title": "Keeping a weather eye", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1541417", "tags": ["border collie", "dog", "dogs", "life", "monday", "pets", "photo", "Photograph"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-04-30 13:16:11", "content": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"713\" caption=\"Rowan, standing behind grass, waiting for the magical flying stick to soar over her head.\"]<a title=\"An Eye on You by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6982516158/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7092/6982516158_3698e56dd2_c.jpg\" alt=\"An Eye on You\" width=\"713\" height=\"800\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">I don't really mind Mondays.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">There, I've said it.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">I rather enjoy the knowledge that if there's a mountain of stuff waiting to be done (and there always is, it's called \"Life\"), I have a full five weekdays to get it tackled before the weekend hits. If you're going to be inundated with work, having the time in which to not only attack it, but contemplate it and plan your approach, makes a significant difference.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Monday mornings are my \"take stock\" time. In truth, I start the process on Sunday afternoon and evening, since I really am not fond of surprises and there's nothing so surprising as hitting Monday morning and realizing that you were supposed to be somewhere important an hour ago.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">So on Sundays, I peak out from between the grasses of the weekend and watch for the flying sticks of Monday.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">That way, come Monday, I don't have to duck.</p>", "categories": ["apropos of nothing", "dogs", "Life", "photo", "photography"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 18:06:35", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2608", "title": "Melting", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1650655", "tags": ["life", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "Nikon D70", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "Snow", "spring", "weather"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-04-30 15:36:35", "content": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"Drips falling off the roof, where the afternoon sun melted the morning snow.\"]<a title=\"Melting by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7129008201/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8147/7129008201_7decd0e0f7_z.jpg\" alt=\"Melting\" width=\"640\" height=\"438\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">So much for the 10cm of late snowfall we received this morning. It's almost all gone now, thanks to the glorious strength of the spring sun.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Ah, the joys of playing with fast shutter speeds (1/3000 of a second)!</p>", "categories": ["apropos of nothing", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "photo", "photography", "snow", "weather"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 21:35:15", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2610", "title": "Novelty", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "464085", "tags": ["botanic garden", "Camera", "cape spear", "flowers", "lighthouse", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "Nikon", "Nikon D70", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "photos", "St. John's Newfoundland and Labrador", "Tokina", "Wide-angle lens"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-01 19:05:15", "content": "<p style=\"text-align:center;\">I bought a new wide-angle lens today.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">I've been dithering on it for several months now and, after completing the taxes, finally decided to order it. When I went into the camera store, they actually had one in stock, so I was (completely unexpectedly) able to walk out with it, along with a <a class=\"zem_slink\" title=\"UV filter\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UV_filter\" rel=\"wikipedia\" target=\"_blank\">UV filter</a> to protect it, in-hand.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"I've almost given up on taking pictures of the <a class='zem_slink' title='Cape Spear' href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Spear' rel='wikipedia' target='_blank'>Cape Spear</a> lighthouses. It's so difficult to get an original angle and they've been photographed to death. Finding a reflection was a new perspective on this for me, though, so I took a chance.\"]<a title=\"To the lighthouse by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7133346209/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7104/7133346209_d3a06954e4_c.jpg\" alt=\"To the lighthouse\" width=\"640\" height=\"800\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"<a class='zem_slink' title='Erica carnea' href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erica_carnea' rel='wikipedia' target='_blank'>Erica carnea</a> and an archway of logs (butterfly homes) at the Memorial University of Newfoundland's Botanic Gardens.\"]<a title=\"Spring Beckons by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7133343423/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7066/7133343423_a2cb152639_z.jpg\" alt=\"Spring Beckons\" width=\"640\" height=\"365\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">It's a <a href=\"http://www.tokinalens.com/products/tokina/atx116prodx-a.html\">Tokina\u00a0 AT-X 11-16mm f/2.8 PRO DX</a> for Nikon and is an absolute joy to use. The way I often shoot is quite premeditated; I generally pick my locations and shots well before I put the camera to my eye. I usually scout out weather, topography, angles, vegetation and all manner of other relevant details, before I head out to take pictures. What this means is that I have in my head a picture that I want to make and I then have to wrangle the gear and angles to turn my vision into a reality. It's very much how I work with textile art pieces, too.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"Lungworth and windflower, an apt pairing for a breezy day at the Memorial University of Newfoundland's Botanic Gardens.\"]<a title=\"Lungworth and windflower by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6987261886/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7183/6987261886_2dc4460d46_z.jpg\" alt=\"Lungworth and windflower\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">In any event, I often find that the lens that I need encompasses more area than any of the lenses I have available to me. I shoot a lot of landscapes, architectural features and such and the dramatic sweep of sky or ocean behind a focal object is greatly enhanced by being able to include more of that sweep. I have a rapidly growing mental list of shots that I have said, \"Yeah, I'll have to come back and take that with a wide-angle lens.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">My selection of the Tokina was based on <a href=\"http://www.kenrockwell.com/tokina/11-16mm.htm\">reviews</a> and also on surveying the photos taken by others whose work I see as somewhat similar to my own. It's a lens that will outlast the current camera I'm using (Nikon D70) and will be useable with future upgrades to my camera body. It's fast, crisp and a delight to use (although I'm still getting used to exactly how much extra expanse I have at my disposal now).</p>", "categories": ["creativity", "nikon D70", "photography", "photos"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 00:52:23", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2612", "title": "Proof positive...", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "476556", "tags": ["50mm", "border collie", "dog", "moss", "Nikon D70", "pets", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "photos"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-01 22:22:23", "content": "... that he does sleep and is quiet.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"Moss demonstrates somnolence in his favourite rocking chair. Why a nervous and high-strung dog prefers a rocking chair is beyond me.\"]<img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8024/6987793368_63fd1215b9_z.jpg\" alt=\"Somnolence\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" />[/caption]\r\n\r\nSometimes.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"Moss wakes to the sound of a shutter. This shot is taken from his brown side. From his blue side, he looks much more startling. Made with a 50mm lens and available light from a lamp (no flash). \"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7185/7133874537_7a6e9b82e9_z.jpg\" alt=\"Moss\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" />[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"></p>", "categories": ["dogs", "nikon D70", "photography", "photos"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 14:44:41", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2615", "title": "Crawling around on the floor with dogs", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "860713", "tags": ["dog", "life", "Nikon D70", "pets", "photo", "Photography", "photos", "Tokina", "tokina 11-16"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-02 12:14:41", "content": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"457\" caption=\"A border collie in motion tends to go more into motion. Love the low-light capabilities of this lens and how fast it is!!\"]<a title=\"Freeze frame by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7135623917/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7091/7135623917_80dbb1c284_z.jpg\" alt=\"Freeze frame\" width=\"457\" height=\"640\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">To take a bit of\u00a0 a break from work this morning, I hauled out the new lens, snapped it on the camera and stuffed my pockets full of treats.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Suddenly, the subject matter appeared out of nowhere and followed me around the house.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"461\" caption=\"There's nothing like a wide-angle lens to bring out the ears in a border collie!\"]<a title=\"Puppy-faced by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6989539966/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7133/6989539966_9897c09065_z.jpg\" alt=\"Puppy-faced\" width=\"461\" height=\"640\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">The hardest part was keeping the noses off the lens, since you can have this thing a foot from your subject matter. In dog terms, that's equal to a reach of the neck and a swipe of the tongue.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\" caption=\"The expressions are pretty indicative of their personalities. Moss is wanting to be somewhere else and Rowan is flopped over and resigned to staying put until allowed up.\"]<a title=\"Break time by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6989541212/lightbo/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7265/6989541212_100ea35c81_z.jpg\" alt=\"Break time\" width=\"640\" height=\"396\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"></p>", "categories": ["dogs", "nikon D70", "photography", "photos"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 11:41:56", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/2012/05/03/2617/", "title": "", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1940794", "tags": [], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-03 09:11:56", "content": "I'm a huge believer in kids being taught manners and in adults demonstrating them, but I like how this digs yet a layer deeper. Food for thought...", "categories": ["apropos of nothing"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 22:43:05", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2618", "title": "I would like to order.....", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1702704", "tags": ["East Coast Trail", "life", "Middle Cove", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "Nikon D70", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "tokina 11-16", "weather"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-03 20:13:05", "content": "... one of these days:\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a title=\"Middle Cove by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7140228675/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8005/7140228675_6efe5d69fa_z.jpg\" alt=\"Middle Cove\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a> Shagging* around with the new lens a few days ago. It has been foggy, cold and raining ever since.[/caption]\r\n\r\n... but not until Sunday.\r\n\r\n*shagging around = Newfoundland term meaning \"messing about, playing with or otherwise engaged in fiddling around with for the purposes of accomplishing some undefinable, yet vaguely productive, end.\" Not to be confused with the British term \"shagging\", which, while probably the origin of the \"messing about\" definition, has come to mean something a little more direct.", "categories": ["apropos of nothing", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "nikon D70", "photo", "photography", "weather"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-05 20:27:18", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2623", "title": "Between one thing and another", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1156321", "tags": ["canada", "Craft Council of Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "East Coast Trail", "flatrock", "hiking", "life", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "Nikon D70", "photo", "Photograph", "Photography", "photos", "travel"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-05 17:57:18", "content": "<p style=\"text-align:center;\">This weekend has been crazily busy thus far, mostly with Craft Council of Newfoundland &amp; Labrador-related things. The annual Craft Council Seconds Sale was today, as were assorted open studios and craft events that have been collectively gathered under the auspices of \"<a href=\"http://www.craftcouncil.nl.ca/news/may-day-craft-weekend/\">The May Day Craft Weekend</a>\". More on this after I finished editing the photos! Since I was involved with the Seconds Sale, I didn't get around to all the other offerings, but John and Katherine took the camera and the map and visited all but one of the open houses. They had a great time, took some photos, ate things, spent some money (which is really the <strong>best</strong> way for ordinary folks to support craftspeople and artists) and basically had a great Dad &amp; Kid morning.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">After things wound up, I was beat to a snot and couldn't decide whether to drink or sleep. Instead, we opted for a walk out The Beamer (long spit of rock sticking out into the ocean), in Flatrock, to stretch legs, be away from crowds and relax. The fog was doing interesting things, so it looked like it might provide some nifty photo opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a title=\"Broken lines by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7146027833/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5450/7146027833_31451965ed_z.jpg\" alt=\"Broken lines\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a> A broken fence at the start of the trail out The Beamer.[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Of course, as soon as we got out and started walking, the fog began to lift.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a title=\"Erratics I by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6999936610/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7184/6999936610_909c6a222d_z.jpg\" alt=\"Erratics I\" width=\"640\" height=\"394\" /></a> Erratics I[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">So instead of mysterious rocks, shrouded in fog, I have big rocks in the middle of nowhere just sitting there.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a title=\"Erratics II by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/6999935274/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8166/6999935274_d6cb529c72_z.jpg\" alt=\"Erratics II\" width=\"640\" height=\"425\" /></a> Erratics II[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Then we decided to wander along and check on a couple of geocaches of ours that we hadn't visited in a while. In so doing, we stopped past a stream I had <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7126321957/lightbox/\">photographed recently</a>. I took another exposure of it with the new lens, just for interest's sake...</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<a title=\"Spring Stream by VickyTH, on Flickr\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/taylorhood/7146026193/lightbox/\"><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7279/7146026193_a6bd8df3f1_z.jpg\" alt=\"Spring Stream\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /></a> Spring Stream - I very much like the optics and how much of the stream-bed I can get in the frame, but the new lens requires greater proximity, which is not always a good thing near splashing water.[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">More on the rest of the day later. That glass of wine sounds good right about now...</p>", "categories": ["craft", "Craft Council of Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "hiking", "nikon D70", "photography", "photos", "Travel"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-06 12:43:32", "language": "en", "author": "33267", "url": "http://seastrandsstudio.com/?p=2625", "title": "May Day Craft Weekend", "blog": "33272", "post_id": "1889305", "tags": ["Craft", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "photos", "St. John's Newfoundland and Labrador", "studio", "studio tours"], "blogname": "Gone to the Dogs at SeaStrands Studio", "date": "2012-05-06 10:13:32", "content": "I was up to my ears in the organization of the Seconds Sale yesterday, so my deputies took the camera and went off on a Dad &amp; Kid Exploration of the <a href=\"http://www.craftcouncil.nl.ca/news/may-day-craft-weekend/\">MayDay Craft Weekend</a>.\r\n\r\nAll of these photos were taken by John, so any credit is entirely his. I tweaked them here and there (cropping, convert to black and white, that sort of thing, but they're his). I'll let the photos speak to his journey.....\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img class=\" \" src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5117/7001994198_ee7f04b622_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0222\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> The face of a kid when told she's going to be visiting craft demos and studios and the like for the morning.[/caption]\r\n<blockquote><em>Incidentally, a few of the studios and shops are open today as well, so if you're in St. John's, Newfoundland and would like to see some fantastic craft made by some truly exceptional artisans, <a href=\"http://www.craftcouncil.nl.ca/media/uploads/May_Day_Passport_for_web.pdf\">grab a brochure</a> and start your rounds! Don't forget to ask folks to stamp that brochure for you as you go. Four stamps will get you a chance to win a nice basket of professionally-crafted items of all sorts.</em></blockquote>\r\nTheir first stop was <a href=\"http://susanleestudios.blogspot.ca/\">Susan Lee Stephen</a> and her jewellery studio. (Open today as well)\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"512\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7064/7148084691_a79b7865d4_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0232b\" width=\"512\" height=\"640\" /> Susan polishing[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7126/7148084245_7b10bca0d6_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0226a\" width=\"640\" height=\"419\" /> Some new pieces using an etching technique. I love these...[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"426\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7232/7001996644_ce12fe1870_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0235a\" width=\"426\" height=\"640\" /> A corner of Susan's Studio.[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Then they headed down to the Sin City Market (not open today - Saturday event only) and took pictures of the neat things they saw there. Katherine has one of these rocks by the <a href=\"http://www.newfoundlandsoftrockco.com/\">Newfoundland Soft Rock Company</a> and she adores it. Very durable, very cool and quite washable (which matters when you have kids).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7065/7148086961_f5394632d1_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0239a\" width=\"640\" height=\"356\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">And the <a href=\"http://www.gratescovestudios.com/\">Grates Cove Studios</a> folks brought their Xylophone and wooden products...</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5200/7148089271_6e4ee3926c_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0248a\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> Xylophone from Grates Cove[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7247/7002001008_6d15d31690_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0249_049\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> Wooden implements[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7136/7002002458_6480ef637e_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0252a\" width=\"640\" height=\"474\" /> Wooden spinning tops. These are awesome! (Despite the blur, I really like this photo)[/caption]\r\n\r\nJohn came home with a chickadee print from <a href=\"http://jreidstudios.com/\">J Reid Studios</a> which is just exquisite....\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5072/7002006542_e8a2698675_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0255a\" width=\"640\" height=\"472\" /> Jared Reid, of J Reid Studios.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSara Hodder of <a href=\"http://www.sechdesign.ca/\">SECH Design</a> was incredibly photogenic....\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5452/7002008476_1a6059ae28_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0261a\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> ... and makes top-notch clothing, as well![/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7049/7002014516_6f7ffda3d4_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0277a\" width=\"640\" height=\"481\" /> <a href=\"http://www.grahamblairdesigns.com/woodcuts/\">Graham Blair</a>, print-maker of growing repute. His work is beautiful and I have a hunch that collecting pieces now will pay off in the future.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"552\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7123/7002012862_0939de30ab_c.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0274a\" width=\"552\" height=\"800\" /> An assortment of Graham Blair's work. John bought an owl.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAnd there were many, many others there. These are just the ones that John photographed (and of whom the photographs came out okay). The place was pretty crowded with customers, from what I was told.\r\n\r\nThen it was off to the <a href=\"http://www.newfoundlandchocolatecompany.com/index.htm\">Newfoundland Chocolate Company</a> (open Saturday AND Sunday), where tasting was apparently more the focus than was photography. The May Day decor for this location was their usual chocolate mermaid, with clothing (it was a chilly day) in the pink, white and green commonly attributed to the Republic of Newfoundland (those were the theme colours).\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8025/7148104489_1cbafbc2b8_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0286a\" width=\"426\" height=\"640\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">They also stopped by the <a href=\"http://www.craftcouncil.nl.ca/\">Craft Council</a> Shop at Devon House\u00a0(open Saturday AND Sunday) and visited Wendy Shirran, who was demonstrating mug-making using slab building techniques.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7095/7002110682_6c0df2121d_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0320\" width=\"481\" height=\"640\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Then they headed over to the Studio of <a href=\"http://www.alexistempleton.com/\">Alexis Templeton</a> (<a title=\"Visiting Alexis Templeton\u2019s\u00a0Studio\" href=\"http://seastrandsstudio.com/2012/04/23/visiting-alexis-templetons-studio/\">we've been there before</a>), to see what was new.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">(open Saturday AND Sunday)</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"414\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7192/7148112415_50e909e257_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0295a\" width=\"414\" height=\"640\" /> Salt fish designs[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8018/7148108141_8fba582536_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0290a\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> Glassware by <a href=\"http://marcelarosemberg.com/\">Marcela Rosemberg</a> (I believe - correct me if I'm wrong).[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"640\"]<img src=\"http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5339/7148106179_82fbdb7933_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0289\" width=\"640\" height=\"426\" /> An assortment of pottery[/caption]\r\n\r\nAnd finally they went to one of my favourite studios, the printing studio of <a href=\"http://www.runningthegoat.com/main.html\">Running the Goat Books and Broadsides</a> (open Saturday only).\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Katherine thoroughly enjoyed working the big press.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"491\"]<img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7066/7148114175_260b5418c4_z.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_0333a\" width=\"491\" height=\"640\" /> 1830s Imperial Iron Handpress. Very heavy.[/caption]\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"></p>", "categories": ["craft", "Craft Council of Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "creativity", "family", "JohnTH", "KatherineTH", "Newfoundland &amp; Labrador", "photography", "photos"], "likes": []}
