{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 04:57:16", "language": "en", "author": "71880", "url": "http://butchjax.wordpress.com/?p=2124", "title": "One source of frustration", "blog": "72787", "post_id": "1078034", "tags": [], "blogname": "Searching for my truth...", "date": "2012-04-29 22:57:16", "content": "As I was updating my training journal I realized one huge reason I am impatient and frustrated with so many in the Jedi community. This year I can remember less than 7 good days, total, for Carrie. No more than 2 in a row. In 4 full months. Every day is an exercise in resiliency and determination. In spite of everything I carry on a day to day basis, I keep training. Real training. Recognizing my issues, finding ways to work on them, pushing forward. I have all the excuses in the world not to. Yet I still said I have to do better. I added in physical training in spite of the challenge of it, not having time, and not knowing how it would work out. But I did it because it's important for my health. What do most other people seem to do? Sit around their computers, whining. Posting pictures and videos about the same things. Going out drinking with their friends and calling it being a Jedi. None of that shit is training people. None of it. That's sitting around, enjoying the chance to call yourself a Jedi, but not actually working on it. That's not growth.\r\n\r\nSo when I take the time from all the other things I could be doing to try to pass along some knowledge and it gets ignored? That's going to piss me off. It's disrespectful. That's why I left the groups on facebook. I have a big job ahead of me. I take it seriously, and I know that there's not nearly enough time to learn all I need to learn to take on the role I need to take on. So I focus my efforts on training. Maybe in 20 years after all the hard work has been put in some will come crawling back saying they're ready now. And I'll have grown enough to welcome them with a genuine smile. Or I'll have grown the confidence to tell them no, they aren't Jedi knights, and they damn sure aren't Jedi masters. I have no time for people who think they're done, or who only pay lip service to the idea of training.\r\n\r\nAgain, this will sound arrogant. There's no way around that. I see a lot. I look for small growth in people so I can help them see it, encouraging them to continue moving forward rather than grow discouraged. So when I don't see people working on it, I don't see the results in public, I have to question what training they do? And when someone assigns rank to themselves, without any accountability or bonefide training to back it up, no way I'll take them seriously. That has to come through action. There are a few people I view quite highly in the community. Some that while I recognize areas of weakness I believe they are the rank they are. Some who I know are training but end up in situations which show them at their worst. And most who aren't doing anything at all. I have to stop focusing on them. They aren't going to train unless they see the path laid out before them and the difference it makes to do the training. Until there's a truly defined order. And even then, many won't train. They will have dug themselves so deeply into their hole that there's no moving them. It's their choice.\r\n\r\nYeah, that's a bit of a wandering rant.... :-P I feel calmer now though. I will let this go, until something else triggers me and I need to write it out. And piece by piece I will work through this, saying my piece until there's nothing left to say. Then I can really heal whatever is going on.", "categories": ["about me", "Jedi", "Spirituality"], "likes": []}
