{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 18:05:31", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3487", "title": "Short note on the University of Melbourne team at Safi", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "40334", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-04-30 20:05:31", "content": "Louise Hitchcock, leader of the University of Melbourne team at Safi, has sent me a short article that appeared in vol. 8, 2012 of the Bulletin of the Australian Archaeological Institute at Athens, that describes the work of the University of Melbourne team at Tell es-Safi/Gath.\r\n\r\nHere it is: <a href='http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/doc300412-0001.pdf'>DOC300412-0001</a>\r\n\r\nFame and fortune!\r\n:-)\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 05:48:11", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3492", "title": "Nice picture - figurine shelf in the newly organized lab", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "9327", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-01 07:48:11", "content": "Here is a very nice picture of the recently fixed up shelf with various figurines from the excavation. This includes an Iron Age IIB Judahite pillar figurine (back left), two LB plaque figurines (back center), LB bull figurine (back right), Iron I bull figurine (forward left), the painted head of something from the Iron I (2nd to the left forward), a Persian period torso (forward center), and two very interesting Philistine Iron I figurine heads (forward, right).\r\nThe picture in the background is of a plaque figurine mold and a similar plaque from Akko, which was mentioned already in a <a href=\"http://gath.wordpress.com/2009/01/25/an-interesting-find-a-plaque-figurine-mold/\" target=\"_blank\">previous post</a>.\r\n<a href=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/view-of-figurine-group-in-lab.jpg\"><img src=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/view-of-figurine-group-in-lab.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" title=\"view of figurine group in lab\" width=\"1024\" height=\"598\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-3493\" /></a>\r\nCool!\r\n\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 18:24:57", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3498", "title": "Heads up: I'll be in California from January to June 2013 - open for invitations to lecture!", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "180754", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-01 20:24:57", "content": "Just a heads up for those who might be interested, that I will be in California (LA and SD) from early January to early June, 2013, for a half sabbatical (I will be teaching courses first at UCLA and then at UCSD). \r\nDuring that time, I would be more than happy to be invited to lecture on biblical archaeology, the excavations at Tell es-Safi/Gath and similar topics. \r\nIf you would like to coordinate such a lecture(s) (and/or hear more details), do get in touch with me and we'll try to work something out.\r\n\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 16:17:57", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3501", "title": "Waiting for the big news from Qeiyafa....", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "694261", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-02 18:17:57", "content": "Joe Lauer (and <a href=\"http://zwingliusredivivus.wordpress.com/2012/05/02/archaeological-tease-the-valley-of-elah-and-yosef-garfinkels-big-reveal/\" target=\"_blank\">Jim West</a> based on Joe's notice)\u00a0, have sent out the Hebrew University media announcement of a forthcoming press conference next week at which Prof. Yossi Garfinkel of the HU will announce some new important finds at Kh. Qeiyafa, which he believes will have important implications for the study of archaeology, history and the Bible (seems Yossi may have learnt the art of a media tease from me...:-).\r\n\r\nThe bets are on, on what he will announce that he found:\r\n\r\n1) The Philistine foreskins that David took\r\n\r\n2) The bucket of water from the gate of Bethlehem\r\n\r\n3) An inscription mentioning David\r\n\r\n4) An inscription mentioning Goliath\r\n\r\n5) Saul's armor that David did not wear\r\n\r\n6) All of the above\r\n\r\n7) None of the above\r\n\r\nCan't wait until next Tuesday - should be VERY interesting!\r\n\r\n:-)\r\n\r\n<strong>Clarification</strong>: I am told that what will be announced is VERY\u00a0SPECIAL, and I can't wait to see what this is! <em>And Just to clarify - this post was not meant to be critical of Yossi - just to continue along the line of the \"tease\"....</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAren\r\n\r\nP.S. I'm going to try and use my contacts to see if I can find out what it is...", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 14:10:22", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3507", "title": "Just appeared! New article on the formation processes of the Philistine hearths", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "1971866", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-03 16:10:22", "content": "Just got notice that a new article of ours has just appeared, which deals with a study of the formation processes seen in the Philistine hearths.\r\n\r\nThis study is part of Shira Gur-Arieh's dissertation research and congratulations go to Shira for her first article to be published in a <a href=\"http://www.maney.co.uk/index.php/journals/jfa//\" target=\"_blank\">prestigious peer-reviewed journal</a>!!! (see <a href=\"http://gath.wordpress.com/2011/10/13/new-publication-on-experiments-on-how-soot-forms-on-cooking-vessels/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> for a post on other parts of Shira's dissertation that were published as well).\r\n\r\nThis study attempts to understand the formation processes and use of the Philistine hearths, as is explained in the abstract:\r\n\r\n<em>Ancient cooking installations yield important evidence for cooking technology and human diet. A cooking\u00a0</em><em>installation termed the Philistine pebble hearth is associated with the arrival of the Philistines at the\u00a0</em><em>beginning of the Iron Age in the southern Levant (ca. early/mid-12th century B.C.). These installations have\u00a0</em><em>been studied using traditional methods, focusing on a description of form and style in relation to the pottery\u00a0</em><em>of the period. Here we present a study using an experimental approach. We prepared three sets of\u00a0</em><em>experimental pebble hearths to study the pebbles\u2019 thermal behavior in relation to their volume. The\u00a0</em><em>comparison of these results with observations of Iron Age I archaeological hearths reveals different\u00a0</em><em>patterns in pebble shattering and soot patterns, indicating that the archaeological hearths were used in a\u00a0</em><em>different manner than the experimental ones. The experiments highlight the utility of shattered pebbles as\u00a0</em><em>an indicator of the use of fire directly on Philistine hearths, even in the absence of ash and/or charcoal. They\u00a0</em><em>also demonstrate that these installations may have been used with open fire or live embers. The results are\u00a0</em><em>applicable to the study of hearths worldwide, with implications for appropriate excavation methods and\u00a0</em><em>basic identification of ancient pyrotechnologies</em>\r\n\r\nThe article is entitled:\r\n\r\nGur-Arieh, S., Boaretto, E., Maeir, A. M., and Shahack-Gross, R.\u00a02012. Formation Processes in Philistine Hearths from Tell es-Safi/Gath (Israel): An Experimental Approach. <em>Journal of Field Archaeology</em> 37(2): 121\u201331.\r\n\r\nWay to go!!!\r\n\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-04 13:35:58", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3513", "title": "Shira conducting hearth experiments", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "1062852", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-04 15:35:58", "content": "In relation to the new article that just appeared that I mentioned yesterday, Richard Wiskin, our photographer, has sent some very nice pictures from the 2008 season in which you can see Shira conducting some of the hearth experiments discussed in the article.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCheck them out:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-23-tell-es-safi_5031-c.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-3514\" title=\"08.07.23 Tell es-Safi_5031 C\" src=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-23-tell-es-safi_5031-c.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"680\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-24-tell-es-safi_5218-c.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-3515\" title=\"08.07.24 Tell es-Safi_5218 C\" src=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-24-tell-es-safi_5218-c.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"680\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-22-tell-es-safi_4759-c.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-3516\" title=\"08.07.22 Tell es-Safi_4759 C\" src=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/08-07-22-tell-es-safi_4759-c.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"756\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHearth today, gone tomorrow...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n:-)\r\n\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-06 13:49:06", "language": "en", "author": "77347", "url": "http://gath.wordpress.com/?p=3520", "title": "Jill Katz's anthropological view of early Israel", "blog": "78913", "post_id": "100974", "tags": [], "blogname": "The Tell es-Safi/Gath Excavations Official (and Unofficial) Weblog", "date": "2012-05-06 15:49:06", "content": "In the most recent issue of BAR, <a href=\"http://home.yu.edu/faculty/new/default.aspx?id=jckatz\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Jill Katz</a>, who leads the <a href=\"http://www.yu.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">YU</a> <a href=\"http://yu.edu/cis/activities/summer-israel/\" target=\"_blank\">contingent</a> to the Tell es-Safi/Gath excavations, has a piece about her views, as an archaeologist trained with an anthropologically based background, about the social setting and structure of early Israel.\r\n\r\nSee here piece <a href=\"http://www.bib-arch.org/bar/article.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=38&amp;Issue=3&amp;ArticleID=28\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\r\n\r\nCongratulations to Jill!\r\n\r\nAnd just so that you see what team leaders do at Tell es-Safi/Gath, here's a picture of Jill in action:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/10-07-13-tell-es-safi_0398-k60.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-3521\" title=\"10.07.13 Tell es-Safi_0398  K60\" src=\"http://gath.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/10-07-13-tell-es-safi_0398-k60.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"680\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAren", "categories": ["Miscellaneous"], "likes": []}
