{"date_gmt":"2012-05-04 01:02:05", "language": "en", "author": "139752", "url": "http://winereview.wordpress.com/?p=2460", "title": "Boutari Moschofilero 2010", "blog": "140355", "post_id": "459439", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wine Reviews &amp; Comments", "date": "2012-05-04 11:32:05", "content": "80 points\n\nMantinia, Pelopennese, Greece.  11.5%\n\nIn spite of its low alcohol, and high altitude viticulure this is quite an unctuous rich wine with low acid and tinned fruit flavours.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://winereview.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/20120504-111022.jpg\"><img src=\"http://winereview.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/20120504-111022.jpg\" alt=\"20120504-111022.jpg\" class=\"alignnone size-full\" /></a>", "categories": ["White wines"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-04 01:07:16", "language": "en", "author": "139752", "url": "http://winereview.wordpress.com/?p=2463", "title": "Houghton Gladstones Shiraz 2001", "blog": "140355", "post_id": "1930008", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wine Reviews &amp; Comments", "date": "2012-05-04 11:37:16", "content": "91 points\n\nFrankland River, Western Australia.14.5%\n\nClassy wine with some high quality fruit, but the volume is turned up a little too high, too much oak, too much concentration.  Perhaps all it needs is more time, but I'm sure they could have picked a little earlier, extracted a little less, used less new oak and achieved a finer more elegant wine.  Nevertheless it has style and depth - very good wine.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://winereview.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/20120504-110936.jpg\"><img src=\"http://winereview.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/20120504-110936.jpg\" alt=\"20120504-110936.jpg\" class=\"alignnone size-full\" /></a>", "categories": ["Australia", "Shiraz"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 10:35:44", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6484", "title": "Here's Your Future", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1849164", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-04-30 19:35:44", "content": "Laurie Penny reviews <a href=\"http://thenewinquiry.com/essays/the-future-probably/\">William Gibson's latest book a collection of essays</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\"In essays here on Tokyo, on Singapore, on London, Gibson opens the skin of cities like old watches and looks for the peculiar synergy of metal and emotion that makes their gears spin. With each little tick, he sees the future city under the present one, waiting to be brought into being. It\u2019s not really ever about colored hair or robot outfits, but about people and the breathtaking things they have a tendency to do when presented with technology that changes the way they live and communicate.\"</blockquote>", "categories": ["Books", "Politics"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 03:27:44", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6486", "title": "Language Makes Your More Rational", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1988107", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-01 12:27:44", "content": "<em>Wired</em> on how <a href=\"http://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2012/04/language-and-bias/\">\"Thinking in a Foreign Language Makes Decisions More Rational\"</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\u201c'Would you make the same decisions in a foreign language as you would in your native tongue?' asked psychologists led by Boaz Keysar of the University of Chicago in an April 18 <em>Psychological Science</em> study.\r\n\r\n'It may be intuitive that people would make the same choices regardless of the language they are using, or that the difficulty of using a foreign language would make decisions less systematic. We discovered, however, that the opposite is true: Using a foreign language reduces decision-making biases,' wrote Keysar\u2019s team.\"</blockquote>\r\nSomehow I'm not surprised.\u00a0 The benefits of learning a second or third language go far beyond communication (which is no small thing in itself, obviously).\u00a0 Languages are ways of thinking above all else.\r\n\r\nThe whole article is fascinating (much of the research was actually done with native Korean speakers learning English in Seoul).", "categories": ["ESL", "Language"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 05:06:52", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6489", "title": "Gaming The Odds", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "157668", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-01 14:06:52", "content": "A surprisingly lucid examination of <a href=\"http://kotaku.com/5906280/even-our-best-video-games-cant-predict-what-kim-jong+un-would-do-to-win-a-new-korean-war\">using video games to predict the outcome of a North-South Korean war</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\"Yet the caveat here is that while wargaming does best at covering the kinetic side of war\u2014how far can a cannon shoot, how many inches of reinforced concrete can a bunker-buster bomb penetrate\u2014it doesn't tend to cover the 'soft' factors as well. The <em>Raging Tiger</em> game has rules for refugees and collateral damage, but for the most part, these games focus on combat. Yet the South Korean capital of Seoul is within artillery range of the DMZ, and North Korea has the largest artillery force in the world. Surely that will affect Korea's strategic decisions. China may be tired of propping up its unruly North Korean client, but the last time American troops approached the Yalu River, Beijing sent 300,000 'volunteers' to fight them.\r\n\r\nOne reason why wargames were invented was so that commanders wouldn't be surprised by what happened on the real battlefield. But we can pretty sure that whatever happens in Korea, it won't be what we expected.\"</blockquote>\r\nI don't think anyone doubts who would \"win\" this war in a strictly military sense.\u00a0 The question is much more subtle: In what would basically amount to an army-level suicide attack by the North, would South Korean and US air-power be able to annihilate the North's infantry and artillery batteries fast enough to prevent the destruction of Seoul?\r\n\r\nAlso, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_War#China_intervenes_.28October_.E2.80.93_December_1950.29\">China</a>.\u00a0 The article correctly points out that China is less than enthusiastic in its \"support\" for the North Korean regime but when push comes to shove, would they really be willing to share a border with a pro-American Korean government?\r\n\r\nMacArthur famously got this one completely, utterly wrong back in the winter of 1950.\u00a0 It led to the most massive military retreat in modern history.", "categories": ["China", "Korea", "North Korea", "Politics"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 10:51:35", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6495", "title": "Russia = Punk As Fuck", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1993533", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-01 19:51:35", "content": "<a href=\"http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20120501000315\">Noted without comment</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\"Members of a Russian Orthodox organization used holy water to disperse dozens of protesters supporting jailed punk band Pussy Riot in downtown Moscow.\r\n\r\nMembers of the Union of Orthodox Banner Bearers dumped holy water on the protesters Sunday at the Christ the Savior Cathedral in Moscow while chanting 'no Sodom,' RIA Novosti reported Monday.\r\n\r\nThe unsanctioned demonstration was in support of members of the all-female punk group Pussy Riot, who were arrested for playing a song against President-elect Vladimir Putin inside the cathedral in late February. The five band members performed the song, which they called a 'punk prayer,' next to the cathedral's main altar, which is off-limits to the public.\r\n\r\nThe band members could each face up to seven years in jail if convicted on hooliganism charges.\"</blockquote>", "categories": ["Music"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 03:48:41", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6498", "title": "Corporate Music Still Sucks", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1552248", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-02 12:48:41", "content": "Pitchfork interviews <a href=\"http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8809-kevin-shields/?utm_medium=site&amp;utm_source=related-content&amp;utm_name=features\">My Bloody Valentine's Kevin Shields on the re-issues of his catalog</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\"KS: Ownership and control is important, because if you don't own what you do, all sorts of stupid stuff happens to it, and people spend good money on garbage.\u00a0For example, in America, Warner Bros. licensed <em>Loveless</em> and <em>Isn't Anything </em>to Plain Records, and they basically just ripped [the audio] off the CD and put it on vinyl [in 2003]. They did an awful, terrible job. It was done without my permission, and the sound quality was 100% wrong.\u00a0It was a rip off to anyone who bought it.\u00a0But I didn't know anything about it until they were in the shops. We actually got an injunction against it being imported into the UK at the time because it was technically a bootleg but, in America, Warners operate under their own law, so it might have been slightly legal in the United States.\r\n\r\nAlso, you don't get paid if you don't own it-- you know, we've never been paid one penny from the United States from any of the records we've ever made.\u00a0In the record company's world, we're always in debt. But the strange part of the story is\u00a0<em>Loveless</em>\u00a0alone sold enough copies in its first year to put us out of debt. But somehow Warners have managed to create a situation where, hundreds of thousands of records down the line, we're still in debt. That's why the compilations aren't coming out on Warner Bros. They're extremely in breach of contract as well at the moment.\"</blockquote>\r\nThe sooner major record labels die off the better.\u00a0 What a nightmare for any artist.", "categories": ["Music", "Politics"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 10:32:37", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6500", "title": "School Spirit", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1811699", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-02 19:32:37", "content": "My college has Sports Day next week.\u00a0 It\u2019s kind of like the collegiate version of American Field Day, but much more intense.\u00a0 Koreans being hyper-competitive by nature, every department basically goes bug-fuck insane trying to outdo one another.\u00a0 And not just athletically (soccer, basketball, running, pigu) but perhaps more importantly,<a href=\"http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/2012/03/08/scary-cheerleader-squad/\"> the cheer-squads</a> have been practicing for a week now filling the campus with their chanting and occasional screams.\r\n\r\nI\u2019m all for school and departmental spirit, but it seems to get more ridiculous every year.\u00a0 More and more students don\u2019t show up for the class the week before the event, then come crying to me and whining about how they \u201chad\u201d to attend cheer or soccer practice.\u00a0 And these are the same students who will be whining at the end of the semester when they get C\u2019s and D\u2019s on my final.\r\n\r\nSo yeah, I get two days off next week but I\u2019ll have to do make-up classes which are a pain to schedule, and inevitably even more students will \u201cforget\u201d to attend those.\u00a0 That said, Sports Day itself is kind of fun and worth checking out at least once in you\u2019re a foreigner.\u00a0 (Those robotic cheer sections you can see in video from North Korea?\u00a0 Eerily similar.)\r\n\r\nChalk it up as another \u201cI Love You Korea But There Are A Few Things I Will Never Understand About You.\u201d\u00a0 Honestly \u2014 couldn\u2019t they just do this on the weekend instead?", "categories": ["ESL", "Korea", "Sports", "Teaching"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 07:15:53", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6502", "title": "/facepalm", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "253674", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-03 16:15:53", "content": "Dear Departmental Chair X:\r\n\r\nIf you're going to cancel my class, you should probably inform some people.\u00a0 For example, me.", "categories": ["ESL", "Korea", "Teaching", "WhinyForeigner"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 08:03:59", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6505", "title": "\"Fat men in nappies\"", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "1477544", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-03 17:03:59", "content": "<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2012/may/02/charlie-brooker-sumo-wrestling-tokyo\">Charlie Brooker goes to Tokyo for a sumo tournament</a>:\r\n<blockquote>\"The problem is this: to a Westerner, sumo looks inherently silly. Fat men in nappies: that's our gut reaction. Skim a languid eye over it and it scarcely resembles a sport at all. At first\u00a0glance it's an excuse to show off the participants' bodies, with particular emphasis on the buttocks \u2013 a bit like beach volleyball with diabetic coach drivers. At second glance, all that pushing and shoving looks less like a martial art and more like a fight in a pub doorway. There is, of course, rather more to it than that, but you have to sit down and pay attention for\u00a0some time before you unlock it.\"</blockquote>\r\nWhen I lived in Japan I deeply regretted not making it to some live sumo action.", "categories": ["Japan", "Sports"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-04 06:28:08", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6508", "title": "Buddha Is My Copilot", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "65625", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-04 15:28:08", "content": "<a href=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/039.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6509\" title=\"039\" src=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/039.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"853\" /></a>\r\n\r\nDaegu, South Korea.", "categories": ["Daegu", "Korea", "Photography"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-06 07:41:47", "language": "en", "author": "140519", "url": "http://wetcasements.wordpress.com/?p=6512", "title": "Fried Chickengasm With Morrissey", "blog": "141110", "post_id": "91052", "tags": [], "blogname": "Wet Casements", "date": "2012-05-06 16:41:47", "content": "<a href=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/010.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6513\" title=\"010\" src=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/010.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\r\n\r\nI'd been curious about a new restaurant right across from Traveler's called Smith's Chicken.\u00a0 It's a grey block of a building with white letters spelling out, ahem, \"SMITH'S CHICKEN.\"\u00a0 Turns out, they serve chicken.\u00a0 And no, it isn't owned by a guy named Smith, but rather an artsy Korean dude who loves the Smiths and Motown.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/009.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6514\" title=\"009\" src=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/009.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\r\n\r\nMmm, buckets of fried chicken.\u00a0 What could be better?\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/008.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6515\" title=\"008\" src=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/008.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIt's some of the best Korean-style fried chicken I've had (whole bird boned up, not too greasy) and the cocktails were decent.\u00a0 Also, not many people were there so I figured a shout-out might be appropriate.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/006.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6516\" title=\"006\" src=\"http://wetcasements.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/006.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"853\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAnd really, how many restaurants in Korea are classy enough to actually play one of the greatest songs of all time?\r\n\r\n[youtube=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=diadZbYpvGk]", "categories": ["Daegu", "Food", "Korea", "Restaurants"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-04-30 19:00:48", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5702", "title": "Purrfect Places for Puss", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "1709528", "tags": ["Cats"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-01 07:00:48", "content": "Bentley is a curious cat, who loves to explore, and to sleep.\u00a0 One of his favourite spots is my pillow, especially when the morning sun is shining in.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5703\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Why bother getting up?\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-bed_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5703\" title=\"Bentley in bed_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-bed_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nWhen I opened the stationery cupboard he bounded in and curled up there.\u00a0 I couldn't bear to disturb him, and he was still there when I came home three hours later.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5704\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Bentley in cupboard\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-cupboard_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5704\" title=\"Bentley in cupboard_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-cupboard_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI refused to allow him into the bathroom cupboard.\u00a0 He said a very definite 'Hmph' and immediately leapt into the bath.\u00a0 How did he know it wasn't full of water?\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5705\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Bentley in bath\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-bath_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5705\" title=\"Bentley in bath_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/bentley-in-bath_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI can't resist photographing him when he looks so beautiful.\u00a0 Does your cat seek out strange places too?\u00a0\r\n\r\n\"Bentley's a star of blog and screen\r\nwho poses neatly for each scene.\"", "categories": ["Cottage Life"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-01 20:12:18", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5684", "title": "Cones on high", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "1508225", "tags": ["Christchurch", "cones", "earthquake"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-02 08:12:18", "content": "Our ubiquitous road cones appear in strange places.\u00a0 Here's one on Poplar Crescent:\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5685\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"225\" caption=\"Cone on lampstand\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-on-lampstand_480x640.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5685\" title=\"Cone on lampstand_480x640\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-on-lampstand_480x640.jpg?w=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI saw one on a road sign near the beach:\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5700\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"225\" caption=\"Cone at beach\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-at-beach_480x640.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5700\" title=\"Cone at Beach_480x640\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-at-beach_480x640.jpg?w=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nAnd another on the archway of the old Piko building:\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5686\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"225\" caption=\"Piko cone\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-at-piko_480x640.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5686\" title=\"Cone at Piko_480x640\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/cone-at-piko_480x640.jpg?w=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nPeople have been creative to get them up so high.\u00a0 I wonder how long they'll stay there?\u00a0 Will they fall off if there's an earthquake?\r\n\r\n\"How do they get them up so high?\r\nP'raps when a crane is passing by?\"", "categories": ["Central Christchurch", "Earthquake"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-02 18:19:47", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5710", "title": "Area unshackled", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "1468156", "tags": ["Christchurch", "earthquake"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-03 06:19:47", "content": "The section of Oxford Terrace between Madras and Manchester is open once more.\u00a0 You can't go through, just up to the end and back.\u00a0 It felt really strange to walk along this so-familiar path which has been prohibited for more than a year.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5712\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/armagh-oxford-corner_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5712\" title=\"Armagh-Oxford corner_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/armagh-oxford-corner_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Armagh-Oxford Terrace corner[/caption]\r\n\r\nWhere once the Bourbon Rose and Subway stood, there are now weeds.\u00a0 At least Verkerks' building has survived.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5713\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/poplar-crescent_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5713\" title=\"Poplar Crescent_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/poplar-crescent_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Poplar Crescent[/caption]\r\n\r\nPoplar Crescent looks just the same.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5714\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/bohemian_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5714\" title=\"Bohemian_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/bohemian_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Bohemian Cafe and Bar[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Bohemian's doors are boarded up but the building looks okay.\u00a0 The fact that there's no fence around it bodes well.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5715\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/elsie-locke-park_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5715\" title=\"Elsie Locke Park_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/elsie-locke-park_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Elsie Locke Park[/caption]\r\n\r\nElsie Locke Park has been mowed, but the prospect for the Centennial Pool is bleak.\u00a0 The drinking fountain on the riverbank opposite is working, suggesting services in the area are okay.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5716\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"225\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/edmonds-clock-tower_480x640.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5716\" title=\"Edmonds Clock Tower_480x640\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/edmonds-clock-tower_480x640.jpg?w=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a> Edmonds Clocktower[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Edmonds Clocktower has now been fenced and braced.\u00a0 I hope this means it will be preserved.\r\n\r\n\"It seemed so strange to place my feet\r\nonce more upon this well-loved street.\"", "categories": ["Central Christchurch", "Earthquake"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-03 18:42:25", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5722", "title": "Horrible Hackers", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "231288", "tags": ["technology"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-04 06:42:25", "content": "A friend had her e-mail hacked this week, causing inconvenience to her and concern to her contacts.\r\n\r\nAt the same time word came that VolunteerNet's security had been breached.\u00a0 This is the expensive government-backed portal that was set up to be a legacy from the Rugby World Cup.\u00a0 A message sent to users advised that all our contact details and passwords may have been accessed by outsiders with ill intentions.\u00a0 The message pointed out that as many people use the same password for different devices we need to check all of these and change passwords that may be compromised.\u00a0 In the meantime the site's been taken offline.\u00a0 It's used mainly by event managers to recruit volunteers for one-off events, so some of them\u00a0may be severely inconvenienced - luckily they can call on their local volunteer centre for help.\r\n\r\nPersonally I have passwords for about 50 different online 'things' at home, and close to 100 at work, and yes, I re-use some passwords, and I write some down.\u00a0 I'm aware that there are online sites where you can store all your passwords and remember just the one that takes you to that site, but I'm wary of privacy there too.\u00a0 I've resisted online banking, especially since I heard an address from the Privacy Commission pointing out how vulnerable that can be.\u00a0 I'm not sure what I'll do when cheques are phased out in a couple of years.\u00a0 Perhaps by then we'll be able to scan thumbprints or retinas for our online transactions?\u00a0 Or maybe we'll all have 'chips' implanted.\u00a0 Was life easier before the internet appeared?\r\n\r\n\"They're waiting out in cyberspace\r\nand plotting how to take your place.\"", "categories": ["Blogging &amp; Techno thingies"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-05 08:09:13", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5727", "title": "Park Promenade", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "1459754", "tags": ["Christchurch", "leaves", "trees"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-05 20:09:13", "content": "On my way to an appointment in\u00a0Hagley Park's\u00a0Geo-Dome, I had time to crunch\u00a0through drifts of autumn leaves.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5728\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"225\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/leaves-to-crunch_480x640.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5728\" title=\"Leaves to crunch_480x640\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/leaves-to-crunch_480x640.jpg?w=225\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a> Autumn leaves in Hagley Park[/caption]\r\n\r\nI wondered what these hemispherical markers were for.\u00a0 They had SMC written on them - possibly something to do with St Margaret's College?\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5729\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/mysterious-markers_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5729\" title=\"Mysterious markers_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/mysterious-markers_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Mysterious markers[/caption]\r\n\r\nAll the picnic tables were full with people enjoying lunch among the trees.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5730\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lunchers_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5730\" title=\"Lunchers_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lunchers_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Lunching in the park[/caption]\r\n\r\nIt's good to see Lake Victoria with water in it once more.\u00a0 I'm sure the ducks are relieved.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5731\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lake-victoria_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5731\" title=\"Lake Victoria_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lake-victoria_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Lake Victoria[/caption]\r\n\r\n\"It's nice within the park to stroll\r\na pleasure which I here extol.\"", "categories": ["Central Christchurch"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-06 08:00:59", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5742", "title": "Sighting the Supermoon", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "1921322", "tags": ["Christchurch", "moon", "seasons"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-06 20:00:59", "content": "Tonight's the night when the moon is at its perigee - the closest it comes to earth all year.\u00a0 Because it's also a full moon, it's called a supermoon.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5745\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/supermoon_640x4801.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5745\" title=\"Supermoon_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/supermoon_640x4801.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Supermoon[/caption]\r\n\r\nAlthough the sky was cloudy the moon could be seen quite clearly.\u00a0\u00a0\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/supermoon-through-trees_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5746\" title=\"Supermoon through trees_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/supermoon-through-trees_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n\u00a0I thought it looked more dramatic through trees, but my camera automatically focussed on the leaves rather than the moon.\u00a0 There's likely to be higher tides than usual, but we're not expecting werewolves.\u00a0\r\n\r\n\u00a0\"A full moon is a super sight\r\nthat's coming closer in tonight.\"", "categories": ["Central Christchurch", "Seasons &amp; Cycles"], "likes": []}
{"date_gmt":"2012-05-06 18:43:34", "language": "en", "author": "140573", "url": "http://realruth.wordpress.com/?p=5736", "title": "Alice's (re) Appearance", "blog": "141162", "post_id": "103475", "tags": ["Christchurch", "film"], "blogname": "Ruth&#039;s Reflections", "date": "2012-05-07 06:43:34", "content": "<a title=\"Alice in Videoland\" href=\"http://www.aliceinvideoland.co.nz/\">Alice in Videoland</a> is open\u00a0again.\u00a0 They have an amazing range of\u00a0films and shows on video and dvd.\u00a0\u00a0Alice has\u00a0moved to the back of the art deco post office building on the corner of High and Tuam Streets, and a coffee bar will occupy the front.\u00a0 It's wonderful that this building has survived when so many nearby have gone.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_5738\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/alice-in-videoland_640x480.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-5738\" title=\"Alice in Videoland_640x480\" src=\"http://realruth.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/alice-in-videoland_640x480.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> Alice in Videoland[/caption]\r\n\r\nWe hired the Christmas Special of Downton Abbey, which we'd missed during our TV-free months, and thoroughly enjoyed it.\u00a0 I look forward to many more evenings' entertainment from Alice.\r\n\r\n\"There's no d v d you will lack\r\nnow that\u00a0Alice our friend is back.\"", "categories": ["Central Christchurch", "Films &amp; shows"], "likes": []}
